{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17583080","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17583080"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T07:06:43+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T07:06:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1968"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1968","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1968"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1968"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78839"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1968","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1968"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1968"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64188"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4944"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"743"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27046"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78839","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78839"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with three days of productive cough, fever, and shortness of breath. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, she appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 125/75 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, SpO2 94% on room air, and temperature 38.5\u00b0C. Chest examination reveals right lower zone crackles. A chest X-ray shows right lower lobe consolidation. Gram stain of sputum reveals Gram-negative coccobacilli.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely implicated bacteria?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Haemophilus influenzae","Moraxella catarrhalis","Klebsiella pneumoniae","Legionella pneumophila","Escherichia coli"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical presentation and Gram stain findings are most consistent with community-acquired pneumonia caused by \u003Cstrong\u003EHaemophilus influenzae\u003C/strong\u003E, which characteristically appears as small Gram-negative coccobacilli. This organism is a common cause of community-acquired pneumonia, particularly in adults with underlying lung disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMoraxella catarrhalis\u003C/strong\u003E, while also appearing as Gram-negative diplococci, is more commonly associated with bronchitis and exacerbations of chronic obstructive pulmonary disease rather than community-acquired pneumonia in otherwise healthy adults.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EKlebsiella pneumoniae\u003C/strong\u003E appears as larger Gram-negative rods rather than coccobacilli, and typically causes a more severe pneumonia with thick, bloody sputum and rapid cavity formation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELegionella pneumophila\u003C/strong\u003E cannot be seen on routine Gram stain and requires special culture media or urinary antigen testing for diagnosis. It typically causes a more severe pneumonia with prominent extrapulmonary symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEscherichia coli\u003C/strong\u003E appears as Gram-negative rods rather than coccobacilli, and is more commonly associated with hospital-acquired pneumonia or aspiration in debilitated patients.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe presence of Gram-negative coccobacilli on sputum microscopy, combined with the clinical presentation of community-acquired pneumonia, should prompt empiric therapy to cover \u003Cem\u003EH. influenzae\u003C/em\u003E, typically with a beta-lactam antibiotic.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Haemophilus influenzae is a common cause of community-acquired pneumonia and appears as Gram-negative coccobacilli on microscopy.","Gram stain morphology is a crucial initial step in directing antimicrobial therapy for pneumonia.","Other causes of community-acquired pneumonia include Streptococcus pneumoniae (Gram-positive cocci) and Mycoplasma pneumoniae (cannot be seen on Gram stain)."],"references":["Murray PR, Rosenthal KS, Pfaller MA. Medical Microbiology. 8th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64188"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1968"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64188","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64188"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-12T21:00:05+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-12T21:01:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1968"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78839"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"em